define({"topics":[{"title":"English in the UK","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">Englishes in the UK are separated by isoglosses (geographical dialectal boundaries).         There has also been a 'Great Vowel Shift' that started in the 15th century.<\/p>","href":"englishes\/_c_uk.html","attributes":{"data-id":"c_uk"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"c_uk-d883e671","next":"c_uk-d883e671"},{"title":"Irish English","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">Irish English comprises 3 dialectal areas.<\/p>","href":"englishes\/irish_english.html","attributes":{"data-id":"b1t5_irish_english"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"b1t5_irish_english-d883e715","topics":[]},{"title":"American English","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">There is no single uniform dialect in America. Standard American English is the         standardized English. American Englishes can be divided into 5 major dialectal zones.         America has two well-known accents, the Boston and the New York accent. English in the West         has largely homogenized, whereas English along the coast varies. Immigrants (example         Italians in New York) have diversified English and accents.<\/p>","href":"englishes\/american_english.html","attributes":{"data-id":"b1t5_american_english"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"b1t5_american_english-d883e726","next":"b1t5_american_english-d883e726"},{"title":"Indian English","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">Indian English is an outer circle English. India was colonized by imposition by which         local languages were maintained. English is an administrative language in India. Estimates         claim that there are 33 to 330 million English speakers in India. India has Hinglish, a mix         of English and Indian languages.<\/p>","href":"englishes\/indian_english.html","attributes":{"data-id":"b1t5_indian_english"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"b1t5_indian_english-d883e748","topics":[]},{"title":"Expanding circle and Euro English","shortdesc":"<p class=\"shortdesc\">In countries that belong to the expanding circle, English has no official function,         but is learned as a foreign language and serves as a lingua franca between speakers that         have no common language. This definition is no longer clear-cut, as the case of Finland         shows hwere English is assuming the status of a second language. Euro English is a variety         that is developing among European countries.<\/p>","href":"englishes\/expanding_circle_and_euro_english.html","attributes":{"data-id":"b1t5_expanding_circle_and_euro_english"},"menu":{"hasChildren":false},"tocID":"b1t5_expanding_circle_and_euro_english-d883e759","topics":[]}]});